abstract: This week’s Australia Letter explores the connection between international threats, journalism and technology.
snippet: This week’s Australia Letter explores the connection between international threats, journalism and technology.
lead_paragraph: The Australia Letter is a weekly newsletter from our Australia bureau chief. Sign up to get it by email. Here’s where to find all our Oceania coverage.

abstract: After two terrible events, the finger-pointing keeps getting worse.
snippet: After two terrible events, the finger-pointing keeps getting worse.
lead_paragraph: Welcome to The New York Times’s international election newsletter, where Sarah Lyall tries to explain the U.S. midterm elections to readers outside the United States (and perhaps to herself). Only a week to go.

abstract: The midterms are a referendum on many of the most divisive issues in America; plus, getting out the vote in Texas, and close races in Iowa and N.J.

abstract: Washington State voters will decide next week whether to impose a fee on carbon emissions. We hope they do.

lead_paragraph: Will voters in Washington State breathe new life into the idea of taxing carbon emissions? Plenty of people worried about the earth’s future certainly hope so.

abstract: Cobbling a coalition out of “Lower Alabama,” a Midwest-like midsection, a tropical megalopolis and more can be tricky.

lead_paragraph: TALLAHASSEE, Fla. — After enduring two decades of Republican statewide rule, Florida Democrats are pursuing a novel strategy to reclaim the Governor’s Mansion — one that would have been unthinkable even a few years ago. They are rallying behind a young, unapologetically liberal African-American candidate in a swing state where older conservative white voters have dominated five straight midterms.

abstract: With Republicans confident about holding onto their Senate majority, the party is fortifying defenses in conservative-leaning districts that were considered secure but now may be at risk.
snippet: With Republicans confident about holding onto their Senate majority, the party is fortifying defenses in conservative-leaning districts that were considered secure but now may be at risk.
lead_paragraph: CINCINNATI — As the 2018 midterm campaign enters its final full week, House Republicans are rushing to fortify their defenses in conservative-leaning districts they thought were secure, pouring millions of dollars into a last-minute bid to build a new firewall against Democrats.
